# Scanner-pairing module (realtime)

Layers: components · config.ts (`SOCKET_PATH`, `isMobileScannerEnabled`) · `station-purpose.ts`
(per-purpose copy) · errors (`PairingError extends DomainError`) · hooks (desktop+mobile socket
hooks, `use-pairing-session-query`) · **repositories/** (`pairing.repository.ts` — Prisma here,
e.g. `findSessionUser`) · services (`pairing.service.ts`, `scanner-socket-manager.service.ts`,
`socket-client.service.ts`, `socket-token.service.ts`) · socket (`events.ts` = event contract) · store
(`scanner-pairing.store.ts` = UI only) · types · utils (`resolve-public-origin.ts`) · validators
(`scannedCodeSchema` = lenient scan gate; `pairingPurposeSchema`).

This pairing flow is **reused by 4 stations** — recordings, POS scan-to-cart, New-PO scan-to-order,
and **opname scan-to-count** — kept apart by `PairingSession.purpose` (see below). It is NOT recordings-only.

## 🔒 HAPPY FLOW 2 — Mobile Scanner (behavior MUST NOT change)
desktop shows QR → phone opens `/mobile/connect` (auto sign-in via pairing code) →
socket connects → scan barcode → emit `barcode_scanned` → server relays realtime to desktop
→ desktop prefills resi → duplicate check → **3s countdown** → auto-record.

## 🔒 Socket.IO contract — DO NOT rename/repurpose (events.ts)
client→server: `join_pairing` `leave_pairing` `barcode_scanned` `scanner_heartbeat`
`disconnect_pairing` `report_station_state`.
server→client: `pairing_connected` `pairing_disconnected` `barcode_scanned` `barcode_ack`
`recording_triggered` `station_recording_state` `pairing_error` `session_state`.
Contract names/payloads are unchanged. `recording_triggered` is now **only emitted for a
RECORDING pairing** (server gates on `session.purpose`); the client also no longer reacts to it
to optimistically show the countdown — the phone's station phase is driven authoritatively by
`station_recording_state`, so a duplicate-resi reject leaves the phone scanning (not stuck).

## Pairing purpose (RECORDING | POS | PURCHASING | OPNAME)
`PairingSession.purpose` (Prisma enum `PairingPurpose`) keeps the 4 stations apart so one scan
never fires on the wrong page. `createSession(userId, purpose)` (POST body `{purpose}`, validated
by `pairingPurposeSchema`); the **connect dialog carries a `purpose` prop** and only reuses an
active session when its purpose matches (else mints a fresh one, superseding the other — one active
session per user). Each desktop consumer gates on the active session's purpose
(`activePairing.session.purpose === '…'`) before acting. Copy is purpose-aware via `station-purpose.ts`.
POS/PO scan-to-cart/order live in the **sales / purchasing** modules (`usePosScanner` /
`usePurchaseScanner` + `…/variants/resolve?code=` resolvers); **opname scan-to-count** is
`useOpnameScanner` (inventory module) — each scan tallies **+1** via `POST /inventory/opname/:id/scan`.
See `40-inventory-marketplace.mdc`.

**Hardening (don't regress):**
- **Phone re-auths as the session OWNER on every QR scan** (`useMobilePairingQrAuth`): the pairing-code
  credential sign-in runs even when a *different* account is already signed in on the phone — otherwise a
  stale login made every pairing 403 (`getSessionForUser`/`connectMobile` assert ownership). `isAuthenticated`
  stays false until the claim settles so the connect flow + session GET never fire as the wrong user. This is
  a CLIENT hook calling `signIn` — it does NOT touch Auth.js config (HARD #2).
- **Desktop "connected" indicator is purpose-gated** (`isConnected = displaySession.purpose === purpose && …`)
  so a leftover CONNECTED session of another station doesn't show a false "Ponsel terhubung".
- **The connect URL carries `purpose`** (display-only; the session is still authoritative) so the phone shows
  the right "Menghubungkan ke <station>…" copy before the session loads.
- **Release on leave**: `useReleasePairingOnNavigate(session)` disconnects the purpose-matched session on
  client-side navigation away from a scan page, but PRESERVES it across a full refresh/close (beforeunload /
  pagehide) so a reload re-attaches. Wired into the POS / PO / opname scanner hooks (recordings excluded).

## Scan handling — verbatim codes, formats, history, sound
- **Verbatim**: scanned codes are relayed/stored as-typed (only trimmed). `normalizeBarcodeValue`
  was removed. The lenient **`scannedCodeSchema`** (non-empty, ≤128) gates the camera/socket path so
  a SKU/barcode with any casing/character isn't dropped; the strict resi `noResiSchema` only runs at
  recording-create + manual/hardware-wedge entry. Resolvers match barcode-then-sku case-insensitively.
- **Formats**: the mobile reader (`@zxing/browser`) enables `QR_CODE` **and** the 1D logistics
  symbologies — labels are QR, shipping barcodes are 1D.
- **Reliable history**: every accepted scan is its own history entry (no dedupe-by-value). The camera
  debounces only the code currently in frame and re-arms after `REARM_AFTER_GAP_MS` of no decode, so a
  steady barcode fires once but a deliberate re-scan counts again. The server skips its duplicate guard
  for POS/PURCHASING (re-scan = +1 unit); RECORDING still dedupes one resi.
- **Sound is browser-only** (no phone beep — avoids double): `@/lib/scan-sound` (`playScanSuccess`/
  `playScanError`/`playCountdown*`) + `useSoundUnlock` (unlock Web Audio on first gesture) +
  `useScanSoundPref` (per-station mute, persisted). The recording countdown ticks on the desktop.
- **Mobile UI**: one shared `MobileScannerView` for all purposes (purpose-aware copy), a square
  aim reticle with a sweeping scan-line, and a compact recent-scans list.

## State
Pairing session = **server state → TanStack Query cache** (`use-pairing-session-query`,
socket events write via `setPairingQueryClient`). `scanner-pairing.store` (Zustand) holds
ONLY UI state (countdown/dialog/connection/station phase). Never store the session in Zustand.

## ⚠️ "xhr poll error" — root cause + fix (do NOT reintroduce)
Socket.IO exists ONLY on the custom `apps/web/server.ts` (`initPairingSocketServer`), run by
`tsx server.ts`. The **VPS web container runs it**, so the socket is **same-origin in prod**. A
serverless platform that only builds `framework: nextjs` and **never runs server.ts** (the retired
Vercel) had no `/api/socket` handler → the Engine.IO long-poll handshake went unanswered → `xhr
poll error`. Keep prod on the custom server.
- Forcing `transports: ['websocket']` is **NOT a fix** — serverless can't hold the persistent
  connection / heartbeat sweeps.
- Same-origin needs NO `NEXT_PUBLIC_SOCKET_URL`. Splitting the socket onto a **separate always-on
  host** (scaling) → set it; cross-origin auth uses token-in-handshake (B), no shared cookie domain.
  See `docs/deployment/socket-server.md`. Auth.js cookie / env / socket contract = confirm first.
